Add AttrMorph.prototype.clear and AttrMorph.prototype.destroy.

These methods are called by `renderAndCleanup` (from `template-utils`)
when an AttrMorph is created in a block helpers template:

```javascript
    {{input type="checkbox" checked=checked}}

    {{#if checked}}
      <a href={{"http://google.com"}}>google.com</a>
    {{else}}
      <a href={{"http://yahoo.com"}}>yahoo.com</a>
    {{/if}}
```

In the above example, when `checked` is toggled the `href` AttrMorphs get `.clear()`
and `.destroy()` called on them.

Implement dirtying render with layouts

This change makes it possible for a block helper to delegate the block
it was passed to another template (the "layout").

```js
var layout = compile("<p>{{yield attrs.title}}</p>");
var template = compile(
  "{{#component title={{title}} as |t|}}<span>{{t}}</span>{{/component}}"
);

registerHelper('component', function(params, hash) {
  this.yieldWithLayout(layout, { attrs: hash });
});

// Produces <p><span>Hello world</span></p>
template.render({ title: "Hello world" });
```

The functionality works for block helpers and components, and the
default hooks delegate to overridable scope management hooks to hide
the nitty gritty machinery.

Notably, this also supports idempotent re-rendering as long as the
layout itself is stable.

Pass options through to AST plugins.

This allows AST plugins to have more information about the thing being
compiled. The intent is for this to be a way to provide compile time
template deprecations and still be able to indicate the module path for
the template being compiled.

The general idea is that ember-cli-htmlbars will call `compile`
something like:

```javascript
var compiler = require('./bower_components/ember/ember-template-compiler');

var template = compiler.precompile(input, {
  moduleName: 'some-app/path/to-template/stuff'
});
```

Remove trailing semicolon from generated template.

This semicolon means that we cannot include a compiled template inline
within a class definition.

Specifically the following breaks (needed in Ember) with the semi-colon:

```javascript
export default Ember.HTMLBars.template(
 /* HTMLBars compiled template that has trailing semicolon as below*/
 ;
)
```

Refactor DOMHelper, introduce contextualElement

Template execution now requires both hooks and the dom to be passed in.
For example:

    template(context, {hooks: hooks, dom: new DOMHelper()});

Optionally, you can provide a contextualElement to the DOMHelper. This
will allow it to resolve un-escaped HTML rendering issues:

    var template = compile('{{{html}}}');
    var tableElement = document.createElement('table');
    template({html: '<tr><td>Yo</td></tr>', {
      hooks: hooks,
      dom: new DOMHelper(tableElement)
    });

When block or component hooks are called in hydration, they are passed a
DOMHelper instance with the current contextual element. This allows
templates like:

    var template = compile('<table>{{#test}}{{{html}}}{{/if}}');
    template({html: '<tr><td>Yo</td></tr>', {
      hooks: hooks,
      dom: new DOMHelper(null, document)
    });

To run properly. The `test` helper just needs to pass the env (which
contains the proper contextual element) through to the inner render.

This code also prepares htmlbars for changing namespaces based on the
AST.

